After aggregating the data by playerID, first name, and last name, I am adding some common stats not available in the dataset to analyze players - Batting Average (AVG), On Base Percentage (OBP), Slugging Percentage (SLG), and On Base Plus Slugging Percentage (OBP)¶

In [373]:
# Batting average formula based on Wikipedia formula 
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseball_statistics#Batting_statistics

playerID_od_c['AVG'] = (playerID_od_c['H'])/(playerID_od_c['AB'])

# OBP formula retrieved from
# http://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/On_base_percentage

playerID_od_c['OBP'] = (playerID_od_c['BB'] + playerID_od_c['H'] + playerID_od_c['HBP'])/(playerID_od_c['AB'] + playerID_od_c['BB'] \
                                                                                 + playerID_od_c['HBP'] + playerID_od_c['SF'])

# SLG Percentage to weight a hitter's impact to runs scored
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slugging_percentage

playerID_od_c['SLG'] = ((playerID_od_c['HR'] * 4) + (playerID_od_c['3B'] * 3) +\
                        (playerID_od_c['2B'] * 2) + \
                        (playerID_od_c['H']-(playerID_od_c['2B'] + playerID_od_c['3B'] + playerID_od_c['HR'])))/\
                        playerID_od_c['AB']

# OPS to find total value of player (OBP + SLG)
# http://m.mlb.com/glossary/standard-stats/on-base-plus-slugging 

playerID_od_c['OPS'] = playerID_od_c['SLG'] + playerID_od_c['OBP']

After looking at HOF Catchers' career hitting & fielding, I noticed a major discrepancy: Players that played prior to 1950 that were voted in by committees other than the BBWAA have much different statistics than modern players.¶

For example, Caught Stealing (CS), Zone Rating (ZR), and Sacrifice Flies (SF) are all statistics of the modern game that are not included in each players data set.¶

Because of this, I have decided to remove these players from the data set and to compare players in the modern era that the BBWAA have chosen.¶

To read more about this distinction between players' era and how they are voted into the Hall of Fame, see link below.¶

http://baseballhall.org/news/hall-of-fame-announcements

Post 1949 & BBWAA HOF Players¶

Recreating AVG, OBP, SLG, and OPS for new data set¶

In [378]:
playerID_od_c = playerID_od_c[['G_batting', 'AB', 'R', 'H', '2B', '3B', 'HR', 'RBI', 'SB_batting', 'CS_batting', 'BB', 'SO', \
                           'IBB', 'HBP', 'SH', 'SF', 'GIDP', 'G_fielding', 'GS', 'InnOuts', 'PO', 'A', 'E', 'DP', 'PB', \
                           'WP', 'SB_fielding', 'CS_fielding', 'ZR']]

# Batting average formula based on Wikipedia formula 
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseball_statistics#Batting_statistics

playerID_od_c['AVG'] = (playerID_od_c['H'])/(playerID_od_c['AB'])

# OBP formula retrieved from
# http://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/On_base_percentage

playerID_od_c['OBP'] = (playerID_od_c['BB'] + playerID_od_c['H'] + playerID_od_c['HBP'])/(playerID_od_c['AB'] + playerID_od_c['BB'] \
                                                                                 + playerID_od_c['HBP'] + playerID_od_c['SF'])

# SLG Percentage to weight a hitter's impact to runs scored
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slugging_percentage

playerID_od_c['SLG'] = ((playerID_od_c['HR'] * 4) + (playerID_od_c['3B'] * 3) +\
                        (playerID_od_c['2B'] * 2) + \
                        (playerID_od_c['H']-(playerID_od_c['2B'] + playerID_od_c['3B'] + playerID_od_c['HR'])))/\
                        playerID_od_c['AB']

# OPS to find total value of player (OBP + SLG)
# http://m.mlb.com/glossary/standard-stats/on-base-plus-slugging 

playerID_od_c['OPS'] = playerID_od_c['SLG'] + playerID_od_c['OBP']

Looking at these average stats, they seem a bit low. The average number of hits gives this away as 200-300 hits is close to the average of a starter per season in the modern game. Looking at the average Games Played also gives this away, as 318 Games is a little over two seasons in the MLB. Because of this, I am going to truncate the batting data to only players with 318 Games Played and call this the 'Starter' dataset. Obviously, these HOF players are talented because they stayed in the big leagues for multiple seasons, but I'm curious how they compare to other Starters. Hopefully, this will give a better comparison of players who have played multiple seasons or didn't bounce in and out of the majors.¶

The last two visualizations give a much better analysis of hitters in the MLB post 1949. Looking at these basic hitting statistics, it's interesting to understand each player's strength. Clearly, Craig Biggio was the best player of this group to make contact and get hits, but does that make him the best offensive catcher of this group? Mike Piazza holds the most Home Runs in a career, but not far from him is Johnny Bench who also had more Walks giving him a better OBP.¶

One thing is certain though, these players were some of the best to play compared to their peers, especially compared to other starting catchers.¶

Let's look at stats like On Base Percentage (OBP), Slugging (SLG), and On Base Plus Slugging to understand these catchers' different strengths.¶

In [388]:
# Batting average formula based on Wikipedia formula 
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseball_statistics#Batting_statistics

batting_groupID['AVG'] = (batting_groupID['H'])/(batting_groupID['AB'])

# OBP formula retrieved from
# http://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/On_base_percentage

batting_groupID['OBP'] = (batting_groupID['BB'] + batting_groupID['H'] + batting_groupID['HBP'])/(batting_groupID['AB'] + batting_groupID['BB'] \
                                                                                 + batting_groupID['HBP'] + batting_groupID['SF'])

# SLG Percentage to weight a hitter's impact to runs scored
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slugging_percentage

batting_groupID['SLG'] = ((batting_groupID['HR'] * 4) + (batting_groupID['3B'] * 3) +\
                        (batting_groupID['2B'] * 2) + \
                        (batting_groupID['H']-(batting_groupID['2B'] + batting_groupID['3B'] + batting_groupID['HR'])))/\
                        batting_groupID['AB']

# OPS to find total value of player (OBP + SLG)
# http://m.mlb.com/glossary/standard-stats/on-base-plus-slugging 

batting_groupID['OPS'] = batting_groupID['SLG'] + batting_groupID['OBP']

It's impossible to objectively determine the best catcher to play in baseball. When looking at the limited offensive & defensive measurements, not one catcher stands above everyone else. It shows how tough it is to be the best, even at your position, in the history of this league.¶

Though there is not one objective best catcher, based on the data supplied, I would recommend that Jorge Posada, Lance Parrish, and Bob Boone could be considered for the HoF based on their similar stats of other catchers in the Hall of Fame. Though none of the players recommended have as strong of resumes as all the players in the HOF. Ultimately, it is not up to me, but the plurality of voters that determine who does and does not make the hall of fame.¶
